payload.summary:
Project Method: Waterfall

## Overview  
- **Project**: CR Perbaikan Remark Settlement QRIS Livin' Merchant  
- **Version**: 1.0  
- **Purpose**: Improve QRIS settlement transaction remark formatting in Livin' Merchant by implementing structured, user-friendly remarks using IRIS-based pattern mapping for better merchant readability.

## Main Users & Features  
- **User Roles**: Livin' by Mandiri individual merchants, corporate merchants  
- **Core Features**:  
  - Restructuring of QRIS settlement transaction remarks  
  - Conditional remark generation based on batch settlement time (05, 13, 17)  
  - Use of EFTRM fields (EFTRM1, EFTRM2, EFTRM3) for structured remark formatting  
  - Fallback to TRREMK for non-standard batches  
  - Integration with IRIS Engine for pattern-based remark service

## How It Works  
- **Main Workflow**: For transactions with KOTRAN 7873 and TRNCD 1 or 5, the system checks EFTRM3 for batch values (05, 13, 17); if matched, builds a formatted remark using merchant MID, name, and batch time from EFTRM fields; otherwise defaults to TRREMK.  
- **Key Business Rules**:  
  - If EFTRM3 value is 05, 13, or 17 → generate remark as "Pencairan QR ke [EFTRM1] [EFTRM2] [EFTRM3]"  
  - For all other cases → retain original TRREMK content

## Integrations  
- **System Connections**: IRIS Engine (Pattern Remark CASA Service), Core Banking (via CDC/Kafka), Everest CASA Trx History, BDS CASA Trx History, Livin' 2.0  
- **Module Dependencies**: IRIS DB, CASA transaction history systems, settlement batch processing modules

## Notable Issues  
- **Inconsistencies**: None  
- **Known Gaps**: No identified gaps or risks documented

## Keywords (Consolidated)  
remark, settlement qris, pattern remark, eftrm, qris livin, batch cair, casa service, merchant, kotran 7873, iris, core banking, trremk, transaction formatting, batch processing

Project Method: Agile

## System Overview  
- **System/Module**: Work Flow Management System (WFMS) – Operation Request Portal 2025  
- **Version & Status**: Multiple versions (v0.1 to v1.1), Final baselines for Release 2.0 and 3, Agile methodology  

## Core Technical Approach  
- **Main Components**:  
  - Pega-based workflow engine managing case lifecycles (Create → Initiate → Validation → Approval → Posting/Release)  
  - Core modules: Bulk Account Opening (Perorangan/Badan), Mandiri Auto Debit, Pengajuan Uang Muka, DSR/GSR, Product Code Change, KCM Onboarding  
  - Standardized Case ID formats (e.g., BAOP-YYMMDDnnnn) with daily reset  
  - Parallel validation (data, host, fraud, CIF), TAT/TAI tracking, decision history  
  - Kanban-style UI with stage visualization and configurable routing  
- **Main Processing**:  
  - Case initiation with pre-filled user data from CTO-UserMapping; multi-stage validation and role-based approval routing; integration-driven posting with retry logic.  
- **Key Validations**:  
  - Mandatory field checks (Jenis Permohonan, Tipe Transaksi, Kewarganegaraan)  
  - User access and role validation via CTO-UserMapping (including TellerID–Cabang match)  
  - CIF, duplicate (MDM), fraud (AFAS), and consent (CMS) checks during validation  

## System Integrations  
- **Connected Systems**:  
  - EMAS/eMAS (SOA & FTP) – CIF inquiry, account posting, fund booking  
  - DMS (Documentum) via CMIIS – document upload, view, delete  
  - SI (System Integrator) – Fee Interbranch processing, scheduler logic  
  - MFT/FTP – file transfer for Mandiri Auto Debit, eMasTxt  
  - SAP FICO – GL posting (Pengajuan Uang Muka, Fee Interbranch)  
- **Security/Standards**:  
  - HTTPS/TLS for all integrations; JWT for API authentication; AES encryption (data at rest/in transit); role-based access via CTO-UserMapping or UAM  

## Technical Issues  
- **Known Gaps**:  
  - Deferred SAP FICO integration for GL posting and reversals (Uang Muka)  
  - Incomplete error handling for EMAS/eMAS, MFT, and host posting (partial/batch failures)  
- **Implementation Risks**:  
  - High integration complexity with SOA, FTP, and SI systems; dependency on external systems (AFAS, SAMS, CMS)  
  - Inconsistent or missing retry, timeout, and failure recovery logic across modules  
- **Technical Inconsistencies**:  
  - EMAS integration described via SOA and FTP inconsistently across docs; some specify SOA-only, others include FTP. SAP FICO usage referenced but not uniformly detailed.  

## Keywords (Consolidated)  
wfms, pega, bulk account opening, emas, dms, si, sap fico, mft, ms teams, cto-usermapping, case lifecycle, data validation, host validation, soa, jwt, https, aes encryption, approval workflow, scheduler, reversal logic, document upload, mdm, cms, afas, sams, fee interbranch, uang muka, product code change, kcm onboarding

Project Method: Agile

## Overview  
- **Project**: Operation Request Portal 2025  
- **Version**: 1.0, Final  
- **Purpose**: Automate and streamline Powercash correction, transfer, inquiry, acceleration, and Powerbill registration/cancellation processes within the ICS module, reducing manual effort and improving operational efficiency through integration with ORP, CIS, MICS, and Reborn systems.

## Main Users & Features  
- **User Roles**: CCG Inputer/Agent, CCG CCDM/Supervisor, ECO Pelaksana, SO ECO, SH ECO, Credit Card Holder  
- **Core Features**: Powercash correction & transfer, STP Powercash inquiry, Percepatan Pelunasan (with/without penalty), Powerbill Host-to-Host registration/cancellation, TC posting (601, 162, 163), end-of-day processing, status lifecycle management (P → S → C)

## How It Works  
- **Main Workflow**: Users initiate requests via ORP or OA; verified data triggers automated workflows in ICS for Powercash or Powerbill actions; CIS and MICS support acceleration and inquiry; EOD batch posts TCs and updates statuses.  
- **Key Business Rules**: 1-digit stop code from KTSPKD required; data must match across systems before posting; SO/SH ECO approval needed for critical actions; TC 162/163 posted conditionally based on penalty rules; status must be 'S' before EOD processing.

## Integrations  
- **System Connections**: ICS, CIS, MICS, OA, Reborn/Rebom, ORP  
- **Module Dependencies**: ICS depends on CIS for acceleration triggers, MICS for execution, OA for data input/log, and Reborn for data synchronization

## Notable Issues  
- **Inconsistencies**: DOC 2 and DOC 3 refer to "Rebom" while DOC 1 uses "Reborn" — likely same system with naming variance.  
- **Known Gaps**: Persistent risk of data mismatch between OA, ICS, and MICS; manual Excel reformatting blocks RPA; email-based requests prone to loss; lack of real-time integration increases error and delay risks.

## Keywords (Consolidated)  
powercash, ics, orp, cis, mics, oa, reborn, rebom, stp, percepatan pelunasan, koreksi, transfer, powerbill, registrasi, pembatalan, tc 601, tc 162, tc 163, stop code, eod, status lifecycle, data verification, host to host, rpa, data mismatch, manual reformatting, so eko, sh eko, ccg, ecopelaksana, cardholder

Project Method: Agile

## System Overview  
- **System/Module**: Operation Request Portal 2025 (ORP Portal)  
- **Version & Status**: Multiple versions (v0.1–v1.3), baselines across Releases 2.0 to 6 (ECO2501010/ECO250101125A), Draft to Final status per module  

## Core Technical Approach  
- **Main Components**:  
  - ORP as central orchestration layer for financial corrections, Power Cash/Bill, WAPU, Cross Control, and Kliring Warkat Debet  
  - CIS for agent-facing ticket creation, PC Inquiry, and workflow initiation  
  - RPA for SFTP-based bulk file processing (Non-H2H, DPII, provider integrations)  
  - SOA/API400 as integration backbone to ICS, Host, eMAS, BI FAST, BPS 2.0  
  - SSO via Red Hat SSO/Keycloak with AD/LDAP for authentication  
- **Main Processing**:  
  - Automated request routing, validation, and status tracking across financial, compliance, and disbursement workflows; real-time (e.g., BI FAST) and batch (EOD, SFTP) processing modes  
- **Key Validations**:  
  - 16-digit credit card number, tenor range (1–36), transaction ID formats (e.g., WAPU-YYYYMM-XXXX-BPS)  
  - Name matching via Jaro-Winkler scoring, account eligibility, file naming/structure (e.g., .DPII, CRC, header-body match)  
  - Cut-off time enforcement, mandatory field checks, dynamic approver mapping  

## System Integrations  
- **Connected Systems**:  
  - ICS (via REST/SOA/IF400) – Card inquiry, reversal, settlement  
  - CIS – Ticket creation, Promote logic, retry workflows  
  - SOA/API400 – Host, eMAS, BI FAST, BPS 2.0, IRS, DWH  
  - RPA – SFTP file exchange with providers, SPK-BI, BDS  
  - SSO (Red Hat SSO/Keycloak) – AD/LDAP, MCAP, CMS, DMS, CBAS  
- **Security/Standards**:  
  - HTTPS/TLS for APIs, SFTP/FTPS for file transfers, JWT/OpenID Connect for SSO  
  - LDAP/AD for identity, SSL offload at LTM, AES encryption implied for DMS  

## Technical Issues  
- **Known Gaps**:  
  - Full credit card numbers displayed in UI (critical security risk)  
  - Manual reconciliation processes still active (BPS 1.0, Berita Acara upload)  
- **Implementation Risks**:  
  - ICS/Host service dependency with undefined error handling and callback logic  
  - RPA as single point of failure; no automated recovery for failed file transfers  
- **Technical Inconsistencies**:  
  - Mixed use of HTTP (insecure) and HTTPS across modules; some SDs specify TLS, others show HTTP in production context  

## Keywords (Consolidated)  
orp portal, power cash, power bill, cis, ics, soa, api400, sso, rpa, sftp, ftps, bi fast, bps 2.0, emas, host, irs, dwh, etl, datastage, gl reconciliation, pemindahbukuan, wapu, cross control, post facto control, dpii, jaro winkler, jwt, openid connect, ldap, ad, keycloak, red hat sso, ssl offload, f5, oracle rac, retry logic, status reversal, credit card parameter

## Product Portfolio Overview  
- **Total Products/Initiatives**: 1  
- **Portfolio Maturity**: 100% FINAL  
- **Timeline Window**: Q1 2025  

## Strategic Business Context  
- **Portfolio Vision**: Enable full data sovereignty and operational control of the Livin' Merchant platform by migrating from Azure Cloud to BMRI On-Premise Data Center, aligning with Bank Mandiri’s Closed Loop Digital Ecosystem and internal governance standards.  
- **Core Business Problems**: Offshore data hosting causing compliance and security risks; vendor dependency; lack of integrated monitoring and support under Bank Mandiri’s infrastructure.  
- **Target User Groups**: F&B and retail merchants, Bank Mandiri internal teams (IT, Risk, Compliance), distributors, payment partners.  

## Product Portfolio Composition  
- **Product Categories**: On-Premise Migration, POS (F&B & Retail), Ordering Value Chain, Lending/Talangan, Multi Outlet Management, Back Office Operations  
- **Number of Epics/Initiatives**: 7  
- **Scope Summary**: End-to-end migration of Livin' Merchant to on-premise infrastructure with integrated POS, self-ordering (QR Table, Kiosk), working capital financing (Dana Talangan), and multi-outlet management, ensuring backward compatibility and secure integration with EDC, QRIS, e-Wallets, and distributor systems.  

## Business Value Drivers  
- **Primary Business Objectives**: Achieve data localization and full system control; ensure compliance with internal security and operational standards; enhance merchant digital experience through unified sales, ordering, and financing tools.  
- **Key Success Indicators (Portfolio-level)**: 10% Dana Talangan adoption among eligible merchants; successful onboarding of EDC and non-EDC merchants; zero critical defects post-migration.  
- **Expected Portfolio Benefits**: Strengthened data security and regulatory compliance; reduced third-party infrastructure dependency; improved merchant engagement via seamless, integrated digital operations.  

## Resource & Timeline  
- **Total Resource Estimate**: 22 FTEs  
- **Portfolio Timeline**: Target release Q1 2025 (R3.1)  
- **Key Dependencies**: UAT validation, CISO and Compliance approvals, data reconciliation, fallback plan (DMP) execution  

## Product Priorities & Synergies  
- **High Priority Products**: On-Premise Migration (critical for compliance and control), Dana Talangan (drives merchant engagement and revenue), Multi Outlet Management (supports scalability for growing merchants)  
- **Product Synergies**: POS, QR Table, and Kiosk features integrate to streamline customer ordering and payment; Dana Talangan links financing directly to supplier payments within the ordering flow.  
- **Related/Dependent Products**: All features depend on successful on-premise migration and secure API integration with payment and distributor platforms.  

## Portfolio Risks & Considerations  
- **Top Portfolio Risks**: Data loss or extended downtime during migration; performance degradation; operational disruption due to compatibility issues.  
- **Risk Mitigation Areas**: Data backup and reconciliation, penetration testing, regression testing, capacity planning, and clear stakeholder communication during transition.  
- **Strategic Dependencies**: Alignment with Bank Mandiri’s security policies, successful CISO sign-off, and stable integration with external payment and distribution networks.  

## Keywords (Consolidated)

Project Method: Waterfall

## Overview  
- **Project**: Merchant App 2025  
- **Version**: 1.0  
- **Purpose**: Enhances Livin Merchant with settlement automation, fraud detection, loyalty incentives, and revenue sharing reconciliation to improve operational efficiency, risk control, and merchant engagement.

## Main Users & Features  
- **User Roles**: Merchant, Fraud Reviewer, Back Office Operator, RPA System, IRS Application, Teller (EVE group), XLS Admin  
- **Core Features**:  
  - File-based settlement and repayment processing  
  - Real-time and batch fraud checks via AFAS/Splunk  
  - Loan writeoff and collectability verification  
  - Revenue sharing reconciliation (GL 18, GL 27561118)  
  - Loyalty point generation and redemption for cashiers  

## How It Works  
- **Main Workflow**: External systems (MTI, Splunk) trigger batch or real-time processes via MFT/SOA; fraud, loan, and settlement data are validated across AFAS, eMAS, and IRS; RPA automates responses like fund holds or merchant suspension; loyalty and reconciliation engines process transaction data for rewards and reporting.  
- **Key Business Rules**:  
  - Fraud results (HFP/Suspect) require manual review; Clean proceeds automatically.  
  - Credit-side GL entries treated as negative; open items carry forward up to 2 days.  
  - Fund hold triggered only by Splunk email with specific subject format.  

## Integrations  
- **System Connections**: AFAS, eMAS (Core Banking & Loan), SOA Biru (API Gateway), MFT, RPA (UiPath), Splunk, IRS, XLS, IRIS, MTI, Kafka/Optic, GLRECON, BPS 2.0  
- **Module Dependencies**:  
  - Fraud checks depend on AFAS and Splunk integration  
  - Settlement and reconciliation rely on MTI and MFT file transfers  
  - Loyalty processing requires CIF validation and campaign setup in XLS  

## Notable Issues  
- **Inconsistencies**: Some documents specify Kodtran 8163 for teller disbursement, while others reference Kotran 4099/4654—potential transaction code variance.  
- **Known Gaps**: Dependency on external MTI development noted in settlement module; no resolution plans documented.

## Keywords (Consolidated)  
settlement, repayment, mft, soa, emas, afas, fraud check, rpa, splunk, revenue sharing, reconciliation, glrecon, loyalty, poin, livin merchant, api gateway, sftp, onboarding, card dongle, merchant onboarding, loan inquiry, automated suspension, hold amount, xls, iris, mtidata, kotran, cdd, multi outlet, cif, campaign, edc, kafka, optic, irs, real-time processing, batch processing

## Program Goals  
- **Main Problems Being Solved**: Fragmented, manual operational processes across business units result in inefficiencies, slow turnaround times, and lack of centralized oversight, hindering customer experience and operational control.  
- **Top Objectives**:  
  - Achieve Zero Operations in business units by centralizing and automating workflows.  
  - Standardize and digitize BOC and custody operations for improved efficiency and compliance.  
  - Enhance customer experience through faster processing and reliable service delivery.  
- **Expected Benefits**: Reduced operational costs, improved compliance and auditability, and increased process efficiency through automation and centralization.

## Users & Success  
- **Key Stakeholders**:  
  - **Business Units**: Require operational relief to focus on sales and customer engagement.  
  - **Back Office (BOC)**: Central team responsible for processing and approving operational workflows.  
  - **Operations Leadership**: Drives standardization, cost efficiency, and operational excellence.  
- **Main User Types**:  
  - Branch/Unit Staff (request initiators)  
  - BOC Officers (workflow processors/approvers)  
  - Operations & Custody Teams (task executors)

## What's Needed  
- **Top Capabilities**:  
  - End-to-end digitization of BOC workflows with automated approvals and performance monitoring.  
  - Centralized custody operations including asset servicing and settlement processing.  
  - Bulk account opening and maintenance via Straight-Through Processing (STP).  
  - Automated host parameter updates (e.g., holidays) integrated with eMAS.  
  - Single Sign-On (SSO) for unified access to operations systems.

## Scope  
- **Main Focus**: Digitization and centralization of BOC, custody, and account management workflows; integration with eMAS, BaNCs, and SAP FICO; implementation of SSO and STP capabilities.  
- **Not Included**: Development of new core banking systems, changes to accounting journal entries, full system redesigns of eMAS/BaNCs, or integration with external third-party platforms beyond defined workflows.

## Keywords (Consolidated)  
orp, boc, custody, stp, sso, parameter automation, operational excellence, wholesale, onboarding, workflow automation, centralized operations, agile

Project Method: Waterfall

## System Overview  
- **System/Module**: Merchant App 2025 (Livin Merchant Ecosystem)  
- **Version & Status**: Multiple modules at v1.0–1.1; Baseline/Final status across components  

## Core Technical Approach  
- **Main Components**: API Gateway (SOA Biru), MTI, eMAS Core Banking, Livin Merchant, UiPath RPA, MFT/SFTP services, IS Corebank/OMNI integration services  
- **Main Processing**: Orchestration via API Gateway for transaction, loan, and loyalty flows; automated merchant suspend via RPA; batch settlement and reconciliation using SFTP/MFT and DB-to-DB logic  
- **Key Validations**: CIF/account/loan status validation (eMAS), filename format & duplicate checks (settlement), input sanitization (special chars, path traversal), GroupID and UI element presence (RPA), HMAC and header validation (APIs)  

## System Integrations  
- **Connected Systems**: eMAS (CFACCT, LNMAST), MTI, CoreBank (SOA Biru), AFAS, IRIS, DECOS, ICS, Splunk (email trigger), Back Office Livin Merchant (UI automation), Staging Server (SFTP), DWH, E-Wallet/Telco/VISA/Mastercard (external)  
- **Security/Standards**: API Key + HMAC-SHA256 + X-SIGNATURE/X-TIMESTAMP headers; TLS 1.2+; HTTPS; AES-256 encryption; QRadar SIEM; LDAP/Windows Credentials (RPA); no OAuth 2.0/2FA (internal justification)  

## Technical Issues  
- **Known Gaps**: FrmsAcquirerSendNmon deferred; hardcoded credentials risk (eMAS); no image/Citrix support in RPA; UI dependency in BO LM automation  
- **Implementation Risks**: UI fragility in RPA flows; non-compliance with OAuth 2.0 and 2FA standards; dependency on external system stability (MTI, BO LM)  
- **Technical Inconsistencies**: Mixed authentication models—API Key only (SOA/internal), vs. Windows Credentials (RPA); some docs state "ready" while others note security non-compliance or pending CSCC

## Overview  
- **Project**: Merchant App – Livin Merchant Release 3.1  
- **Version**: 1.0–2.0 (multi-module)  
- **Purpose**: Enhances the Livin Merchant platform for UMKM merchants with scoring for teaser lending, KUM-TP financing eligibility, secure file transfer, reconciliation of KIOSK transactions, CASA balance validation, and enriched settlement processing.

## Main Users & Features  
- **User Roles**: UMKM Merchants, Merchant Owners, IRS/Reconciliation Officers, System Operators (EDA, MFT, LOS)  
- **Core Features**: Merchant scoring (daily/monthly), whitelist validation, secure file transfer (MFT/SFTP), KIOSK transaction reconciliation, CASA balance inquiry, settlement fund transfer (code 8163), enriched transaction remarks, banner flagging (Hide/Progress/Ajukan)

## How It Works  
- **Main Workflow**: Big Data (EDA) computes merchant scores based on POS/ordering transactions, validates against LOS whitelist, and sends results via MFT to Livin Merchant. Simultaneously, IRS reconciles KIOSK GL and transaction data from Mandiri HOST and MTI via MFT. CASA balance is validated via Open API before credit usage, and settlement is processed via Host Teller with enriched remarks in IRIS.  
- **Key Business Rules**:  
  - Daily scoring: ≥20 POS transactions with ≥100k sales in 30 days  
  - Monthly scoring: ≥3M sales/month for 3 consecutive months (POS: 20 pts, Ordering: 40 pts)  
  - Banner display: “Hide” (ineligible), “Progress” (not whitelisted), “Ajukan” (eligible & whitelisted)

## Integrations  
- **System Connections**: EDA (Big Data), LOS (Pega), MFT, SFTP, MTI, IRS, Mandiri HOST (GLRECON/GLMAST), Open API, Host Teller, IRIS, SOA Corebank, LDAP, SMR  
- **Module Dependencies**: Scoring depends on LOS whitelist and EDA; IRS depends on MTI and MFT; settlement depends on Open API and Host Teller; banner logic depends on scoring and whitelist status

## Notable Issues  
- **Inconsistencies**: DOC 1 and DOC 2 focus on scoring and whitelist with slight variation in point allocation logic; DOC 3 and DOC 4 introduce unrelated modules (settlement, KIOSK reconciliation) without clear integration points to scoring.  
- **Known Gaps**: No unified view of how scoring, settlement, and reconciliation modules interact; banner logic not extended to KIOSK or settlement features.
